SIMPLE: forgive
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forgive
<hw>For*give"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Forgave</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Forgiven</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Forgiving</conjf>]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>forgiven</ets>, <ets>foryiven</ets>, <ets>foryeven</ets>, AS.
<ets>forgiefan</ets>, <ets>forgifan</ets>; perh. <ets>for-</ets> +
<ets>giefan</ets>, <ets>gifan</ets> to give; cf. D. <ets>vergeven</ets>,
G. <ets>vergeben</ets>, Icel. <ets>fyrirgefa</ets>, Sw.
<ets>f<?/rgifva</ets>, Goth. <ets>fragiban</ets> to give, grant. See
<er>For-</er>, and <er>Give</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To give wholly; to make over without reservation; to
resign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To them that list the world's gay shows I leave,⟦br⟧
And to great ones such folly do <qex>forgive</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give up resentment or claim to requital on
account of (an offense or wrong); to remit the penalty of; to pardon; --
said in reference to the act forgiven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And their sins should be <qex>forgiven</qex> them.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark iv. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>forgive</qex> injures so readily that he might be said to
invite them.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cease to feel resentment against, on account of
wrong committed; to give up claim to requital from or retribution upon
(an offender); to absolve; to pardon; -- said of the person
offending.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Father, <qex>forgive</qex> them; for they know not what they
do.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xxiii. 34.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I as free <qex>forgive</qex> you, as I would be
<qex>fforgiven</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Sometimes both the person and the offense follow as
objects of the verb, sometimes one and sometimes the other being the
indirect object. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Forgive</xex> us our debts as we
<xex>forgive</xex> our debtors.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Matt. vi. 12.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Be
of good cheer; thy sins be <xex>forgiven</xex> thee.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Matt.
ix. 2.</au></note></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>excuse</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forgiveness</ent>⟦br⟧
